HB 891 Reengrossed 2026 Regular Session Jacob Landry
Abstract: Reallocates revenue generated by certain special prestige license plates and
creates the "Conserve Louisiana" special prestige license plate and provides for the
issuance, design, implementation, fees, distributions, and promulgation of rules
applicable to these plates.
Present law requires the Dept. of Public Safety and Corrections (DPS&C), office of motor
vehicles (OMV), to establish the La. Quail Forever special prestige license plate for La.
citizens, bearing a picture of a quail on the logo. Further requires a charge of $26, which
must be assessed every two years in addition to the regular fee charged under present law.
Additionally specifies that revenues from the additional $26 fee must be deposited
immediately upon receipt in the state treasury. Further requires the state treasurer place an
amount equal to those revenues in the Conservation Fund, after complying with the
requirements of present law, and must credit that amount to the "quail account" which is
created within the Conservation Fund.
Present law requires 5% of the net proceeds from the $26 be used to promote the existence
of the La. Quail Forever prestige license plate and its availability for use on passenger
vehicles.
Proposed law requires the dept. collect an annual royalty fee of $50 for this special prestige
license plate and be disbursed in accordance present law. Further requires this fee be in
addition to the standard motor vehicle license tax imposed by present law, and a handling
fee of $3.50 for each plate to be retained by the dept. to offset a portion of administrative
costs.
Proposed law requires the dept. collected $50 annual royalty fee be forwarded to La. Quail
Forever and used solely to support the activities of the La. Quail Forever. Further requires
the purchaser of the plate be classified as a member of the La. Quail Forever and will receive
an annual membership.
Present law requires the DPS&C, OMV, to establish the Ducks Unlimited special prestige
license plate for La. citizens, with the color and design selected by the organization
requesting the plate, pursuant to present law. Further requires the charge for the plates be
$50 imposed by present law. Additionally requires the state treasurer place an amount equal
to those revenues in the Conservation Fund, after complying with the requirements of
present law, and must credit that amount to the "waterfowl account" which is created within
the Conservation Fund. Further requires the funds be used solely for the purpose of
conserving, restoring, and enhancing migratory waterfowl habitat in La.
